circumstances.circumstancesOfDisappearance:
The Boyle Couty Sheriff’s Department is asking for the public’s help on a 24-year-old missing cold case. It was on Nov. 19, 1992 that Anna Lee Manning of Junction City, Kentucky was last seen. Her aunt, she saw Anna standing in front of the Chinn’s Jewelry shop on North Third Street that day when she shouted out to her aunt and said she had something to tell her.  Elsie never found out what it was, because she never saw Anna again.  A 1995 article stated that her Aunt did not know where Anna lived after she married her husband, Anthony Manning in 1985.

The Advocate-Messenger ran an article that stated a Anthony B. Manning, 25, of 148 Spring Valley Road turned himself into the police after his wife signed a warrant for his arrest for kidnapping.  According to the article he showed up at his estranged wife apartment with their daughter and ended up handcuffing her and led her out the back door but she was able to escape to a neighbor’s house and called the police.  Anthony served 192 days in jail.

circumstances.circumstancesOfDisappearance:
After a day on the lake, he wandered away from family members at the Grayson Lake Marina parking lot area at about 6:30 pm.  Rich was at the playground with his wife, and grandchildren.  He began walking back towards the marina, his wife and grandchildren following behind.  He was a little bit ahead of them and walked towards the bathroom.  His wife and son walked up to the bathroom to check on him, but Rich was not in the bathroom.  Within 10 minutes of him walking in that direction, family and DNR officers were searching the area for him.  Additional officers from Carter Co. Sheriff's office and Kentucky State Police arrived within the hour and began searching as well.  An Emergency Response Team was on site that evening and searched into the early morning hours.  They continued the search the rest of that week using dogs, foot teams, UTV's, sonar, divers and helicopters.  Additional search teams canvased the area in the following weeks.  Area hospitals and homeless shelters have been contacted.  Local news stations have been running the story. Flyers have been put up in the surrounding areas as well as shared through social media.  The detective, Jeff Kelly, has not received any calls with tips or leads on this case.  The searches have not discovered any clues thus far.  They going to search the dam discharge area and grates the first weekend in October when it can be safely done.  

Richard suffers from early onset frontal lobe dementia and is mostly non-verbal.  He can speak but often does not choose to.
